Stationarity during REM sleep in Old Adults
Priestley-Subba Rao test for weak stationarity
Nine Old Adults [3 m, 6 w; age=67.3+5.5] were volunteer to
register one night polysomnography (PSG): EEG from the 19 scalp
loci of the 10-20 system, plus 2 electrooculogram (EOG) and 1
bipolar EMG at submentionan muscle. MEDICID 5 equipment
Data was organized as 30 s epochs, then REM sleep was visually
Data was filtered to remove trends and periodic components, by
using STL algorith[], then PSR test was performed over every epoch
aviable [approx. 1 hour per subject]. Epochs which failed to be
REM sleep is characterized as it exhibits low voltage mixed frequency
EEG activity, muscular atonia and rapd eye movement.
Weak stationarity is found to be statistically less present on EEG
records during REM sleep, compared to the rest of night sleep. This
result suggest weak stationarity as to help in automatic detection
of REM sleep by quantitive means.
